description.narrative:
Myanmar is unlike any other country in the world – unique in its challenges, unique in its opportunities. After many years of isolation, the country opened its doors to th world in 2012. 

Paradoxically, it may be exactly these decades of isolation that can become their unique factor in accelerating development. Already from the beginning, the TU Delft and IHE Delft became active in Myanmar - building a trustful relationship with the Yangon Technological University (YTU) ,the Myanmar Maritime University (MMU) and their related government departments.

One of the main projects was the NICHE program which laid the first stepping stones for educational change in integrated water resources management (IWRM). While admirable progress has been made by both universities, it is now time to use this foundation and the carefully built relationship for realising more impact. To ensure sustainable uptake and educational change, the continuation of this cooperation is

crucial. 

Therefore, this proposal will:

- continue the educational and institutional strengthening of YTU and MMU in the field of IWRM;
- further enhance the use of innovative and smart technologies for data collection (“leapfrogging”)to support the educational transition to a more practical, entrepreneurial and student-centred way of teaching;
- create linkages between Myanmar, SE Asian and Dutch scientists, professionals, young experts and students for an optimal exchange of technical and didactical knowledge; 
- reap the benefits of the trustful relationship that was built. All partners have learned a lot and possess very valuable knowledge - now that we trust and understand each other, it is time to continue the implementation to achieve real impact together.
